Climate activist Greta Thunberg has narrated how they were detained as they were peacefully protesting the expansion of a coal mine in Germany. She said they were however let go in the evening adding that it was not a crime to protect the climate. "Yesterday I was part of a group that peacefully protested the expansion of a coal mine in Germany. We were kettled by police and then detained but were let go later that evening. Climate protection is not a crime," she tweeted. According to the BBC, Thunberg had been protesting with activists seeking to stop the abandoned village of LÃ¼tzerath from being demolished for the expansion of a coal mine. Police said Thunberg was part of a group that "rushed towards the ledge" of the Garzweiler 2 mine.